article.headline: Claxton scores 27 in win
article.linkText: Warriors deafen Nuggets with victory Claxton
article.story:
OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Speedy Claxton sure can catch you off guard. The 5-foot-11 fireplug scored 17 of his career-high 25 points in the fourth quarter and the short-handed Golden State Warriors snapped Denver's three-game winning streak with a 96-87 victory Friday night. "I'm a quiet guy," Claxton said. "I guess teams might overlook me, but once the game starts I don't think they overlook me anymore." Claxton also had six assists, five rebounds and even a blocked shot in 41 minutes, going 13-of-13 at the free throw line in the final period while playing in place of injured point guard Nick Van Exel. Claxton's fourth-quarter outburst marked the most points in one period by a Warriors player this season. "People underestimate his competitive nature because of the kind of personality he has," Warriors coach Eric Musselman said. "He's just a quiet competitor." Brian Cardinal had 14 points and 11 rebounds in his first career start as the Warriors won their fifth straight home game. Erick Dampier recorded his 27th double-double with 14 points and 14 rebounds. Rookie Carmelo Anthony scored 24 points to lead Denver, the sixth time in seven games Anthony has scored 20 or more points. The Nuggets had a chance to complete a season sweep of their four-game series with the Warriors, but couldn't find any offensive rhythm. Golden State played without Van Exel, who's nursing a left hip pointer, and Mike Dunleavy after the second-year forward hurt his left ankle last Friday against Chicago. He has missed three straight games. "We're a wounded animal tonight," Musselman said before the game. "Hopefully we'll react like wounded animals react -- feisty and unhappy." Dampier certainly had such moments. He scored six points and grabbed seven rebounds in nine minutes of action in the first quarter, but sat most of the second before checking back in 2:33 before halftime with two fouls. He was visibly upset and antsy on the bench. Last season, the 6-foot-11 center called Musselman "Musselhead" out of frustration at his lack of playing time. Yet Musselman has repeatedly commended Dampier for his positive attitude this season. Dampier and Nene were whistled for a double-technical foul in the third quarter for shoving and arguing. Dampier was upset after Nene put a hard hit on Cardinal moments earlier. Denver called timeout with 8:31 left after Calbert Cheaney's basket gave the Warriors a 75-64 lead. Cheaney then converted two free throws to cap a 10-0 run, and the Nuggets didn't get closer than eight points the rest of the way. "It was a lack of everything," Denver's Jon Barry said. "It was a lack of rebounding, poor defense, poor shooting and a lack of offensive execution." The Warriors led by as many as 17 early. All five Golden State starters scored in double digits -- Jason Richardson added 15 points and Cliff Robinson had 15 points, six assists, five rebounds, three steals and two blocked shots. Lately, Van Exel has been sitting more than he's been playing. He was activated from the injured list last Sunday after a struggle with left knee inflammation, then played 14 minutes at Memphis on Monday and 20 minutes Tuesday at Dallas before his hip began bothering him. Van Exel missed his 16th game of the season because of injury. The Nuggets started the game 0-for-6 as the Warriors jumped out to a 13-0 lead. Denver shot 27.8 percent to Golden State's 43.5 percent and fell behind 23-12 after the first quarter. But Musselman subbed liberally and Denver kept cutting down its deficit and pulled to 39-34 at halftime. The Nuggets shot 38.8 percent for the game to Golden State's 42.1.

Game notes
Cardinal recorded his second career double-double. ... While Musselman wouldn't say whether he voted for Anthony for the All-Star game, he hinted it. Musselman believes a player's selection should be about this season's performance only and not past success. "I think Carmelo's a franchise-changer," the coach said. "If a guy is a franchise-changer, he's going to be an All-Star for many years. That's how I feel about Carmelo." ... Oakland Athletics manager Ken Macha attended the Warriors' morning shootaround after being invited by Musselman, who attended an A's game as Macha's guest last season. ... The Nuggets shot 13 first-half free throws to just two for the Warriors. ... Claxton's 13 fourth-quarter free throws without a miss were one off the NBA record for a quarter set by the Warriors' Rick Barry at New York on Dec. 6, 1966. The last player to make 13 straight free throws in a quarter was Shawn Kemp, when he did it in the first quarter on Nov. 6, 1999.
